(43, 21, 1, 43, 6, 1, 1, 'the sea of Tiberias', 'Connection of Locations', 'Both passages mention the sea of Tiberias, linking the locations of Jesus'' ministry. This connection highlights the geographical significance of the sea in the narrative.', 'keyword', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 1, 40, 28, 16, 16, NULL, 'Disciples Gather at Sea', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of the disciples in a specific location after Jesus'' resurrection. John 21:1 mentions the sea of Tiberias, while Matthew 28:16 refers to a mountain in Galilee, indicating a significant post-resurrection meeting.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 1, 43, 6, 23, 23, 'sea of Tiberias', 'Connection Between Tiberias References', 'Both passages emphasize the Sea of Tiberias, linking the location of Jesus'' post-resurrection appearance to the earlier miracle of feeding the multitude. This connection highlights the significance of Tiberias in the ministry of Jesus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 1, 40, 26, 32, 32, NULL, 'Resurrection and Galilee Connection', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' post-resurrection appearances. John 21:1 describes Jesus showing himself to the disciples at the sea of Tiberias, which aligns with Matthew 26:32''s mention of his intention to meet them in Galilee after his resurrection.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 1, 41, 16, 7, 7, 'shewed he himself', 'Post-Resurrection Appearances', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' appearances to the disciples after his resurrection. John 21:1 mentions Jesus showing himself again, while Mark 16:7 indicates he will meet them in Galilee.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 2, 40, 4, 21, 22, 'sons of Zebedee', 'Discipleship and Calling', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of Simon Peter and the sons of Zebedee, highlighting their roles as key disciples. This connection illustrates the continuity of their discipleship from the initial calling to their later gatherings with Jesus.', 'parallel', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 2, 43, 4, 46, 46, 'Cana in Galilee', 'Connection through Cana of Galilee', 'Both passages emphasize Cana of Galilee, linking the disciples'' presence in John 21:2 to Jesus'' earlier miracle in John 4:46. This connection highlights the significance of Cana as a location in Jesus'' ministry.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 2, 6, 19, 28, 28, NULL, 'Connection of Names and Places', 'This connection highlights the presence of specific names in both passages. In John 21:2, the names of disciples are mentioned, while Joshua 19:28 lists geographical locations, suggesting a thematic link between individuals and their respective places.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 2, 42, 5, 10, 10, 'sons of Zebedee', 'Discipleship of Peter and Zebedee', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of Simon Peter and the sons of Zebedee, highlighting their roles as disciples. This connection illustrates their partnership in fishing and their subsequent calling to become ''fishers of men.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 3, 42, 5, 5, 5, 'caught nothing', 'Fishing and Fruitlessness', 'Both passages emphasize the experience of fishing all night and catching nothing. This connection highlights the theme of struggle and the call to trust in Jesus'' word.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 3, 40, 4, 18, 20, 'fishing', 'Fishing as a Metaphor', 'Both passages emphasize fishing, linking Peter''s initial profession to his later calling. The act of fishing in both contexts serves as a metaphor for discipleship and evangelism.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 3, 53, 3, 7, 9, NULL, 'Work and Labor Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of labor and effort in both passages. In John 21:3, Peter and others worked all night fishing but caught nothing, while in 2 Thessalonians 3:7-9, Paul emphasizes working with labor and travail to set an example.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 3, 52, 2, 9, 9, NULL, 'Labour and Night Work Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of laboring through the night. In John 21:3, the disciples fish all night without success, while in 1 Thessalonians 2:9, Paul speaks of laboring night and day to preach the gospel.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 3, 12, 6, 1, 7, 'I go a fishing', 'Theme of Going and Seeking', 'Both passages emphasize the act of going forth to seek something. In John 21:3, Peter and others go fishing, while in 2 Kings 6:1-7, the sons of the prophets go to the Jordan to gather materials.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 3, 46, 3, 7, 7, 'I go a fishing', 'Fishing and Spiritual Growth', 'This connection highlights the theme of effort in both passages. In John 21:3, the disciples'' fishing symbolizes human effort, while 1 Corinthians 3:7 emphasizes that true growth comes from God, not human actions.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 3, 44, 18, 3, 3, 'I go a fishing', 'Connection of Occupation and Activity', 'This connection highlights the theme of work and occupation in both passages. In John 21:3, Peter and others return to fishing, while in Acts 18:3, Paul stays with tentmakers, emphasizing their shared craft.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 4, 43, 20, 14, 14, 'knew not that it was Jesus', 'Recognition of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of not recognizing Jesus at first. In each instance, the disciples and Mary encounter Jesus but do not initially know who He is.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 4, 42, 24, 15, 16, 'knew not that it was Jesus', 'Recognition of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the disciples'' inability to recognize Jesus. In John, the disciples ''knew not that it was Jesus,'' while in Luke, ''their eyes were holden that they should not know him.'' This connection highlights a theme of divine concealment in recognizing the resurrected Christ.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 4, 41, 16, 12, 12, 'knew not that it was Jesus', 'Post-Resurrection Appearances', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus appearing to his disciples in different forms after his resurrection. Both passages describe moments when the disciples did not immediately recognize Jesus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 4, 42, 24, 31, 31, 'knew not that it was Jesus', 'Recognition of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the moment of recognition of Jesus by the disciples. In John 21:4, the disciples do not initially recognize Jesus, while in Luke 24:31, their eyes are opened, and they know him.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 5, 50, 4, 19, 19, 'any meat', 'Provision and Supply Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of provision, as both passages address the idea of needs being met. In John 21:5, the disciples express a lack of food, while Philippians 4:19 assures that God will supply all needs.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 5, 50, 4, 11, 13, 'have ye any meat?', 'Contentment in Need', 'This connection highlights the theme of contentment in both passages. In John 21:5, the disciples express a lack of physical sustenance, while Philippians 4:11-13 discusses being content regardless of circumstances, including hunger.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 5, 19, 37, 3, 3, NULL, 'Provision and Trust in God', 'This connection highlights the theme of being fed and trusting in God for sustenance. In both passages, the idea of being provided for is central, with Jesus asking if the disciples have food and the Psalmist encouraging trust in the Lord to ensure one will be fed.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 5, 42, 24, 41, 43, NULL, 'Connection of Jesus and Food', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus asking for food, highlighting his physical presence and interaction with his disciples after resurrection. This connection illustrates the continuity of Jesus'' ministry and his concern for their needs.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 5, 58, 13, 5, 5, 'have ye any meat?', 'Contentment and Provision', 'This connection highlights the theme of reliance on Jesus for provision and contentment. In both passages, the disciples'' lack of meat and the call to be content with what one has reflect a deeper trust in Jesus'' presence and care.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 5, 62, 2, 13, 13, 'Children', 'Connection of Children in Faith', 'This connection highlights the term ''children'' used in both passages. In John 21:5, Jesus addresses the disciples as ''Children,'' while 1 John 2:13 refers to ''little children'' in a spiritual context, emphasizing their relationship with God.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 6, 42, 5, 4, 7, 'cast the net on the right side', 'Miraculous Catch of Fish', 'Both passages emphasize the miraculous catch of fish following Jesus'' command to cast nets. In each instance, the disciples experience an overwhelming abundance of fish, demonstrating the power of Jesus'' word.', 'theme', 0.46099999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 6, 44, 2, 41, 41, 'ye shall find', 'Miraculous Provision and Growth', 'This connection highlights the theme of miraculous provision leading to abundance. In John 21:6, the disciples experience a miraculous catch of fish, while in Acts 2:41, the result of Peter''s preaching leads to the addition of three thousand souls, showcasing divine abundance in both instances.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 6, 43, 2, 5, 5, NULL, 'Obedience to Instruction', 'This connection highlights the theme of obedience to divine instruction. In both passages, the characters respond to guidance—fishing on the right side and following Mary''s directive to serve.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 6, 44, 4, 4, 4, 'ye shall find', 'Miraculous Provision and Belief', 'This connection highlights the theme of miraculous provision leading to belief. In John 21:6, the abundance of fish signifies divine intervention, while Acts 4:4 shows that many believed after hearing the word, suggesting a similar transformative experience.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 6, 58, 2, 6, 9, NULL, 'Divine Provision and Human Response', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine provision in both passages. In John 21:6, the disciples receive an abundant catch of fish through obedience, while Hebrews 2:6-9 emphasizes God''s care for humanity and the glory bestowed upon Jesus, who fulfills God''s plan for salvation.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 6, 19, 8, 8, 8, NULL, 'Connection of Fish and Sea', 'This connection highlights the theme of abundance in both passages. John 21:6 describes a miraculous catch of fish, while Psalms 8:8 mentions ''the fish of the sea,'' emphasizing God''s creation and provision.', 'theme', 0.286, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 6, 40, 7, 27, 27, NULL, 'Connection of Obedience and Consequences', 'This connection highlights the theme of obedience leading to results. In John 21:6, the disciples'' obedience to cast the net results in a great catch, while in Matthew 7:27, disobedience leads to the house''s fall.', 'theme', 0.286, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 7, 43, 13, 23, 23, 'whom Jesus loved', 'Connection of Beloved Disciple', 'This connection highlights the identity of the disciple whom Jesus loved, linking him to both passages. In John 21:7, this disciple recognizes Jesus, while in John 13:23, he is described as being close to Jesus.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 7, 40, 14, 28, 29, 'It is the Lord', 'Peter''s Response to Jesus', 'This connection highlights Peter''s immediate reaction to Jesus in both passages. In John, Peter jumps into the sea upon recognizing the Lord, while in Matthew, he steps out of the boat to walk towards Him.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 7, 43, 19, 26, 26, NULL, 'Connection of Beloved Disciple', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between Jesus and the disciple whom He loved. In John 21:7, this disciple identifies Jesus, while in John 19:26, he is present at the crucifixion, highlighting his significance in Jesus'' life.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 7, 47, 5, 14, 14, 'It is the Lord', 'Love and Response to Christ', 'This connection highlights the theme of love and action in response to Christ. In John 21:7, the beloved disciple recognizes Jesus, prompting Peter''s immediate response, while in 2 Corinthians 5:14, the love of Christ compels believers to act.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 7, 19, 118, 23, 23, 'It is the Lord', 'Recognition of the Lord''s Presence', 'This connection highlights the recognition of Jesus as Lord in John 21:7, which parallels the acknowledgment of God''s marvelous works in Psalms 118:23. Both passages emphasize the significance of recognizing divine action.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 7, 22, 8, 7, 7, 'It is the Lord', 'Connection of Love and Recognition', 'This connection highlights the theme of love''s power and recognition. In John 21:7, Peter''s immediate response to recognize Jesus reflects a deep love, while Song of Solomon 8:7 emphasizes that love cannot be quenched or drowned by any force.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 7, 41, 11, 3, 3, 'It is the Lord', 'Recognition of the Lord''s Authority', 'This connection highlights the recognition of Jesus as ''the Lord'' in both passages. In John 21:7, Peter acknowledges Jesus'' presence, while in Mark 11:3, the authority of the Lord is invoked for action.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 8, 5, 3, 11, 11, 'cubits', 'Measurement and Scale in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the use of cubits as a unit of measurement in both passages. John 21:8 mentions ''two hundred cubits,'' while Deuteronomy 3:11 specifies ''nine cubits,'' emphasizing a shared cultural context of measurement.', 'keyword', 0.265, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 9, 11, 19, 5, 6, 'fire of coals', 'Provision and Nourishment', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine provision in both passages. In John 21:9, the disciples find fish and bread, while in 1 Kings 19:5-6, Elijah is provided with a cake baked on coals, emphasizing God''s care for His followers.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 9, 43, 21, 10, 10, 'fish laid thereon', 'Connection of Fish and Bread', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of fish, with the first noting fish laid on the fire and the second inviting the disciples to bring their catch. This connection highlights the significance of the fish in the context of Jesus'' provision and the disciples'' efforts.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 9, 43, 18, 18, 18, 'fire of coals', 'Connection of Coals and Fire', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of a ''fire of coals.'' In John 18:18, Peter warms himself by this fire, while in John 21:9, a similar fire is used to prepare food, linking moments of warmth and sustenance in Peter''s journey.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 9, 40, 4, 11, 11, NULL, 'Divine Provision and Care', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine provision, as both passages depict moments of sustenance and care. In John 21:9, the disciples find fish and bread prepared for them, while in Matthew 4:11, angels minister to Jesus, providing for his needs.', 'theme', 0.3, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 9, 41, 8, 3, 3, 'fish laid thereon, and bread', 'Connection of Provision and Need', 'This connection highlights the theme of provision in both passages. In John 21:9, the presence of fish and bread signifies sustenance, while Mark 8:3 addresses the need for food for those who have traveled far.', 'theme', 0.3, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 9, 42, 12, 29, 31, 'fish laid thereon, and bread', 'Provision and Trust in God', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s provision for physical needs. In John 21:9, the disciples find fish and bread, while Luke 12:29-31 encourages believers not to worry about food and drink, assuring them that God knows their needs.', 'theme', 0.3, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 11, 42, 5, 6, 8, NULL, 'Miraculous Catch of Fish', 'Both passages emphasize a miraculous catch of fish, highlighting the abundance of fish caught. In John, the net is not broken, while in Luke, the net breaks, illustrating different outcomes of divine intervention.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 11, 44, 2, 41, 41, 'great fishes', 'Connection of Abundance and Growth', 'This connection highlights the theme of abundance in both passages. In John 21:11, the net holds ''great fishes,'' while in Acts 2:41, ''about three thousand souls'' are added, illustrating a miraculous growth.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 12, 44, 10, 41, 41, NULL, 'Eating with the Resurrected Christ', 'This connection highlights the shared experience of the disciples who ''did eat and drink with him'' after his resurrection. Both passages emphasize the intimate fellowship with Jesus post-resurrection, reinforcing the reality of his physical presence.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 12, 42, 9, 45, 45, 'durst ask him, Who art thou?', 'Understanding and Fear of Asking', 'This connection highlights the disciples'' hesitation to inquire further about Jesus'' identity and teachings. Both passages emphasize a sense of fear and uncertainty in approaching Jesus, leading to a lack of understanding.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 12, 43, 16, 19, 19, 'Who art thou?', 'Disciples'' Inquiry and Recognition', 'This connection highlights the disciples'' desire to understand Jesus'' identity and teachings. In both passages, there is an emphasis on the disciples'' unasked questions and their recognition of Jesus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 12, 1, 32, 29, 30, 'Who art thou?', 'Recognition of Divine Presence', 'Both passages emphasize the recognition of God’s presence. In John, the disciples know it was the Lord without asking, while Jacob acknowledges he has seen God face to face. This connection highlights the theme of encountering the divine.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 12, 41, 9, 32, 32, 'none of the disciples durst ask him', 'Fear of Asking Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the disciples'' fear of questioning Jesus. In John, they do not ask, ''Who art thou?'' while in Mark, they are afraid to ask about his saying. This connection highlights a common theme of hesitation in understanding Jesus.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 12, 43, 4, 27, 27, 'none of the disciples durst ask him', 'Disciples'' Silence and Curiosity', 'Both passages emphasize the disciples'' unasked questions, reflecting their awe and uncertainty in the presence of Jesus. This connection highlights their struggle to comprehend his identity and actions.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 13, 43, 21, 9, 9, NULL, 'Connection of Bread and Fish', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of bread and fish, highlighting a shared meal that Jesus provides for his disciples. This connection illustrates the continuity of Jesus'' care and sustenance for them after his resurrection.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 13, 44, 10, 41, 41, NULL, 'Post-Resurrection Fellowship', 'Both passages emphasize the act of eating and drinking with Jesus after his resurrection, highlighting the intimate fellowship shared between him and his chosen witnesses. This connection underscores the significance of physical sustenance in affirming the reality of his resurrection.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 13, 42, 24, 42, 43, 'fish likewise', 'Post-Resurrection Meals', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus sharing food with his disciples after his resurrection. This connection highlights the physicality of the resurrected Jesus and his continued fellowship with them.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
